atuin: press Ctrl-r for interactive shell history, or run `atuin search`.
%
backup: copy a file or directory to `<name>.bak` with `backup <path>`.
%
cargo-coupling: inspect Rust dependency coupling with `cargo coupling --help`.
%
doxx: preview `.docx` files in the terminal with `doxx file.docx`.
%
fastfetch: print a system summary with `fastfetch` when you need quick OS and hardware context.
%
fzf: pipe candidates into `fzf` when you are choosing from a list.
%
gh: GitHub PRs and issues are one `gh pr view` or `gh issue list` away.
%
glab: use `glab mr list` and `glab ci status` for GitLab context.
%
glim: open the GitLab CI/CD TUI with `glim`.
%
gurk-rs: when personal Signal TUI support is enabled, start it with `gurk`.
%
jiq: shape JSON interactively with `jiq data.json` or `curl ... | jiq`.
%
mdterm: render Markdown in the terminal with `mdterm README.md`.
%
mqttui: browse MQTT topics with `mqttui --broker localhost`.
%
opencode-shared: launch OpenCode through the shared local server with `opencode-shared`.
%
qpdf: inspect or rewrite PDFs with `qpdf in.pdf --pages . 1-3 -- out.pdf`.
%
rainfrog: connect to Postgres in a TUI with `rainfrog postgres://user:pass@host/db`.
%
rd: search with ripgrep plus delta output using `rd pattern`.
%
sqlx: remember `sqlx migrate run` and `sqlx database create`.
%
tdf: view PDFs in the terminal with `tdf file.pdf`; `/` searches and `q` quits.
%
tsql: try the keyboard-first Postgres CLI with `tsql postgres://user:pass@host/db`.
%
tw: inspect tabular data quickly with `tw data.csv`.
%
zellij: start or attach to terminal workspaces with `zellij` or `zellij attach`.
%
zoxide: jump by frecency with `z dir`, or choose interactively with `zi`.
%
bat: use `bat -p file` when you want a syntax-highlighted `cat`.
%
cyme: modern USB listing is available as `cyme --tree` or the `lsusb` alias.
%
delta: let `delta` make diffs readable when reviewing `git diff`.
%
dust: find disk usage hotspots with `dust` or `dust -d 2`.
%
eza: prefer `eza -la` and `eza --tree` for directory listings.
%
fd: find files with `fd pattern` or narrow by extension with `fd -e nix`.
%
gpg-tui: manage GPG keys with `gpg-tui` when raw `gpg` is too fiddly.
%
htop: use `htop` when process CPU, memory, or tree view matters.
%
ouch: compress and extract archives with `ouch c` and `ouch d`.
%
yazi: open the terminal file manager with `yazi`, or jump through the `y` helper.
%
